## Bureaucratic RAG

Doug Sartori  
I have been experimenting with a technique for working with Large Language Models, or LLMs called “Retrieval Augmented Generation”, or RAG. Tuning your prompts can only take you so far \- in general when you talk to a Large Language Model you’re stuck with the knowledge baked into the model. The basic idea of RAG is to supplement a model’s training with vectorized data \- that’s data that has been processed by what’s called an embedding model that the LLM can access in responding to queries. Embedding translates the text of your document into a set of values that represent the semantic meaning of the text. It’s the cheapest and easiest way to modify a model’s accessible knowledge, with the alternatives being model fine-tuning and the pretraining process itself. 

After achieving some success with my own business documents I thought this would make a good demonstration for the podcast. I looked around for interesting unstructured public data that would make for a simple but useful demonstration project and landed on Health Canada’s [briefing material for the deputy minister](https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/corporate/about-health-canada/proactive-disclosure/briefing-documents/2024-main-transition-e-binder.html). It’s a good candidate because this relatively short, dense document contains an overview of the structure, strategy, and operations of the health bureaucracy. 

If you take this document and load it into the knowledge base of a commercial model like ChatGPT, you can get fairly good value out of it, but smaller LLMs need a lot more hints than their bigger cousins. I wanted detailed, precise insights from a model I can run on a local computer. 

I was aiming for a tool that supports natural-language queries about the structure, operations, strategic goals and challenges of the health ministry. My experience with my own data showed me that the key to getting good results from RAG is adding a lot of hints for the model about which content to load in response to user prompts. Unfortunately, the software landscape for this stuff is currently a bit scattered and immature. 

With that in mind, I built a [Python script](https://github.com/dsartori/process-briefings) to break the document down into logical and physical chunks, breaking up the document into sections logically by splitting at the section headers, then creating appropriate-sized chunks for retrieval. Converting unstructured documents into JSON in this way took a few lines of procedural code. Now that I had the data in a format more friendly to the limited context window of language models I could get to work on adding some value to the data.

Metadata generation can be done with traditional techniques like list-based keyword extraction, but I wanted to use an LLM for this demonstration.

To generate the metadata, each chunk of document text is processed with seven prompts: one for a summary and six to extract keywords across dimensions like policies, organizational structure, and history. I was hoping that building metadata out like this would help the model retrieve more precise, relevant results than I got from just loading my documents in chunks.

I experimented with as few as one and as many as twelve metadata prompts. More is better, but there’s a point of diminishing returns. Hair-splitting ends up making for extremely sparse and / or repetitive data so it’s better to consolidate.

I did some manual cleaning of my source HTML document to remove scripts, menus and other data that has no informative value for our purposes. I’m interested in exploring the limits of smaller models running on low-cost equipment. I’ve got a computer built for this purpose so I ran the script configured to use a small model offered by Alibaba called Qwen2.5. It took about 8 hours to generate a JON file.

 For comparison, I used [nebius.com](https://nebius.com) to prepare metadata with the latest version of the Llama model from Meta. It took about an hour to process and cost me just a bit more than 25 cents to get the processed data back. The resulting metadata was not as high-quality as the output I got locally, which was a little surprising. To be fair, prompt tuning counts for a lot, and I didn’t spend any time testing out different prompts. Nebius also offers access to a larger version of Qwen2.5 than I can run locally, so I also tried it out on this task. The resulting dataset was more compact and contained more precise metadata, which really helps the model provide relevant answers. A small model can produce reasonable results, and if you’ve got to keep your data private it can be attractive, but cloud-based services have the scale to offer a different level of performance at a really attractive price.

Once metadata generation was all done, I loaded the resulting file into the knowledge base of my local model and wrote up a [system prompt](https://gist.github.com/dsartori/35de7f2ed879d5a5e50f6362dea2281b), which is the prompt applied before user prompt to guide the LLM in how to respond. When you read it you’ll see how strongly I am reinforcing the need to avoid hallucinations and unsupported inferences. It’s mostly successful.

The results were highly accurate, enabling precise responses to complex queries. For instance, asking, ‘What is Health Canada’s role in regulating food and drugs?’ produces a detailed explanation citing the Food and Drugs Act and relevant responsibilities. If you’re looking to understand the Canadian health bureaucracy this tool can help. Here’s a sample interaction:  
![][image3]

Since I’ve already generated the data, all three versions I made are included in the [code repository](https://github.com/dsartori/process-briefings). If you want your very own “Health Canada Helper” you only need to give it a home. I’ll drop some bread crumbs for a local implementation but if you don’t want to DIY it, you can grab one of the JSON files out of the repository and load it into OpenAI’s ChatGPT or any other commercial LLM. You’ll get far better results than you would from uploading the raw briefing document. There are detailed instructions in the README file. If you’re comfortable with Docker, Linux, and basic network infrastructure you should be able to get it going.

I encourage data professionals to consider these new tools and take them for a spin \- there’s value for us in there to be found.
